---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by keradus at 2016-04-14T08:39:56Z

General fixers are very generic and could or could not conflict with bunch of fixers depending on configuration of that particular general fixer. I would not bother to mark them as conflicting - if one want to use general fixer he should know what is he doing.

I'm agree that one would be able to generate conflicting ruleset, but that's edge case that would made this PR bigger. I would keep it in few steps.
- introduce basic conflicts check (this PR)
- introduce possibility to mark fixers as conflicting in FixerInterface, thanks to which one could handle conflicts of custom fixers
- introduce heavy logic to check conflicts not by rule names, but also by rule configs

Last two should not be done in this PR, but in new one.
But only if one day we will decide to do it.
I have strong feeling that it would take a bit of time that could be used better, eg adding full support for PHP7.

